<% layout("/layouts/boilerplate.ejs") -%>
<style>
  body {
    background-color: #1a2a44;
    color: #ffffff;
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 20px;
    text-align: center;
    margin-top: 70px;
  }
  h1 {
    font-size: 2.5em;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }
  h2 {
    font-size: 2em;
    margin-top: 20px;
  }
  p {
    font-size: 1.2em;
    line-height: 1.5;
    margin: 10px auto;
    max-width: 800px;
  }
  .section {
    margin: 20px 0;
  }
  .media-container {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 20px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
  .media-item {
    max-width: 400px;
    margin: 10px;
  }
  img {
    max-width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border: 2px solid #ffffff;
  }
  video {
    max-width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    max-height: 300px;
    border: 2px solid #ffffff;
  }
  audio {
    max-width: 100%;
    margin: 10px 0;
  }
</style>
<body>
  <h1>Bhai Sati Das Ji</h1>
  <h2>The Devoted Sikh Martyr</h2>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Early Life</h2>
    <p>
      Bhai Sati Das Ji was born in the mid-17th century in Punjab, the younger
      brother of Bhai Mati Das Ji. Raised in a pious Sikh family under the
      influence of his father, Bhai Hira Nand, he embraced Sikh values from a
      young age.
    </p>
    <div class="media-container">
      <div class="media-item">
        <img src="/media/satiDas.jpg" alt="Bhai Sati Das Young" />
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Family Life</h2>
    <p>
      Bhai Sati Das Ji shared a close bond with his brother Bhai Mati Das and
      their family, which was a hub of Sikh devotion. His family supported his
      spiritual journey and stood by him during his trials.
    </p>
    <div class="media-container">
      <div class="media-item">
        <img src="/media/satiDas.jpg" alt="Bhai Sati Das Family" />
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Contributions to Sikhi</h2>
    <p>
      Bhai Sati Das Ji contributed to Sikhi by living a life of faith and
      service alongside Guru Tegh Bahadur Ji. His dedication helped reinforce
      Sikh teachings during a period of persecution.
    </p>
    <div class="media-container">
      <div class="media-item">
        <video controls>
          <source src="/media/video.mp4" type="video/mp4" />
          Your browser does not support the video tag.
        </video>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Martyrdom</h2>
    <p>
      In 1675, Bhai Sati Das Ji was arrested with Guru Tegh Bahadur Ji. He was
      wrapped in cotton and burned alive in Delhi on November 24, 1675, for
      refusing to convert to Islam. His martyrdom showcased unparalleled
      devotion.
    </p>
    <div class="media-container">
      <div class="media-item">
        <img src="/media/satiDas.jpg" alt="Bhai Sati Das Martyrdom" />
      </div>
      <div class="media-item">
        <video controls>
          <source src="/media/video.mp4" type="video/mp4" />
          Your browser does not support the video tag.
        </video>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Legacy</h2>
    <p>
      Bhai Sati Das Ji's sacrifice continues to inspire Sikhs globally. His
      story is a testament to courage and faith, commemorated in Sikh
      traditions.
    </p>
    <div class="media-container">
      <div class="media-item">
        <audio controls>
          <source src="/media/audio.mp3" type="audio/mp3" />
          Your browser does not support the audio element.
        </audio>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
